{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ace67921-f2de-4161-96fa-29afd34a8a3c","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Scenario | Events |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created → Activated` |\n| Sent to background | `Deactivated → Stopped` |\n| Returned to foreground | `Resumed → Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |\n| iOS background snapshot | `Backgrounding` (save state via `BackgroundingEventArgs.State`) |\n\n> **Tip:** `Backgrounding` is iOS-only and gives you a `IPersistedState` dictionary to save transient data before the OS may terminate the process.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0fddc2a2-a985-4bf3-9ef8-10f7976953c7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for debugging/logging purposes. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development - I can answer this directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":446,"requestId":"7FD1:271EF2:6074909:6946FB8:69F156E0"},"id":"3adad21c-9251-4160-a116-9f2aded37956","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:55:06.496Z","parentId":"c41eb2ce-e96c-4963-9b2